        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We observe dust emission and the redshifted CO(3-2) line simultaneously at band 6. We chose the correlator mode with a 1.875 GHz bandwidth in the frequency domain mode and use four spectral windows in four basebands to maximize the continuum sensitivity with the total bandwidth of 7.5 GHz. The line width of the target is 167 km/s (Hatsukade et al. 2014), and we need the frequency domain mode to examine the line shape. The correlator set-up is the same as used in the cycle 0 observations of this target so that we can easily compare and combine them. 
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>#In order to study the spatial distribution of molecular gas and dust, we use the spatial resolution of 0.09" (500 pc scale). We will compare the properties of the GRB site with other regions in the host galaxy. Our previous observations with a beamsize of 0.7"x0.8" do not resolve the dust emission at the GRB site, and we adopt the the largest angular scale of 0.6". The largest recoverable angular scale of the 12m array configuration exceeds the largest angular structure, and we do not need the ACA. 
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We estimate the required sensitivity from the results of our cycle 0 observations (Hatsukade et al. 2014). The continuum flux density of the GRB site is 140 uJy. By assuming conservatively that the star-forming region with the continuum is resolved into two beams with a higher angular resolution (500 pc), we require the rms noise level of 14 uJy/beam for a 5 sigma detection. This noise level is enough to detect the tentative detection (2-3 sigma) of the continuum emission in the nuclear region with &gt;4-5 sigma. Together with the previous observations, we will obtain deeper constraint on the dust continuum and the CO emission. 
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
