    <prp:abstract>Long-duration gamma-ray bursts (GRBs) are thought to be associated with the explosions of massive stars. A significant fraction of GRB afterglows is optically dark. One possible explanation is dust obscuration, but it remains to be less understood what circumstances produce "dark GRBs". We obtained spatially-resolved ALMA maps of dust continuum and CO emission in the dark GRB020819 host at z=0.41 in cycle 0. We found that the molecular gas-to-dust mass ratio at the GRB site is significantly lower than that of the nuclear region, indicating that the GRB occurred under particular circumstances. However, the spatial resolution of 4 kpc is not enough to resolve the local environment. It is still unclear whether the dust emission is related to the GRB site.

We propose dust continuum and CO observations of the GRB020819 host with a 500 pc resolution. We investigate (i) whether the dust emission actually originates from the GRB site, (ii) the spatial extent of dusty star-forming region, and (iii) dust and molecular gas distribution in the nuclear region precisely. Together with our previous observations, we obtain deep constraint on the amount of molecular gas and the gas-to-dust ratio.</prp:abstract>
